%I A094861 #11 Apr 14 2026 00:44:03
%S A094861 1,2,3,4,6,10,14,24,36,58,88,145
%N A094861 Same as A094859, except that we fix X = 123123123...
%C A094861 Original title referred to A094858, which is about binary strings. I assume A094859 is meant, with the alphabet {1, 2, 3}, rather than the standard ternary digits {0, 1, 2}.
%C A094861 Up to n = 8 at least, this choice does give the same maximum as A094859 with unrestricted X.
%e A094861 For n = 4, L(1231, 2113) = {11, 13, 21, 23} is the maximum number of LCS one can have, hence a(4) = 4.
%Y A094861 Cf. A094858.
%K A094861 nonn,more
%O A094861 1,2
%A A094861 Guenter Stertenbrink (Sterten(AT)aol.com), Jun 14 2004
%E A094861 Definition corrected and a(11)-a(12) by_M. F. Hasler_, Apr 12 2026
